<TEXT>
the state department is raising the 
possibility that romania may be denied us trade benefits because 
of electoral irregularities both during the campaign and on 
election day 
department spokeswoman margaret tutwiler said the issue of 
granting romania most favored nation trade status is under review 
as a result of the alleged abuses 
that status would entitle romania to have the lowest possible 
tariff rates for its us exports the late president nicolae 
ceausescu renounced the trade benefits two years ago because of 
insistent us demands for the protection of human rights as the 
price for continuation of these privileges 
according to some estimates ceausescus action cost romania 
250 million yearly in us exports 
romania receives no us economic assistance but an 80 million 
food aid program was began earlier this year 
official returns from last sundays election showed that acting 
president ion iliescu won 85 percent of the vote and that 
candidates from his national salvation front won almost 68 percent 
in the balloting for the bicameral legislature 
the front has been in charge of romania since the communist 
regime was ousted last december its candidates consist mostly of 
former communists who had a falling out with ceausescu 
ms tutwiler said serious distortions during the campaign 
included organized acts of intimidation and violence directed 
primarily against the opposition candidates and their 
sympathizers 
in addition she said the front had virtually unrestricted use 
of government resources for campaign purposes opposition parties 
meanwhile did not have equitable access to public television and 
were prevented from having reliable delivery of their campaign 
literature 
as for election day irregularities ms tutwiler said there were 
instances of inadequate physical control over ballot boxes 
inappropriate assistance to some voters inside the voting booth 
and questions over the status of certain printed ballots and voter 
identity cards 
she accused the romanian government of failing to take 
sufficiently vigorous steps to remedy the distortions or to 
discourage acts of intimidation and violence 
on the other hand she said that the overwhelming number of 
romanians were able to cast their ballots without visible coercion 
we lack substantiating evidence that these voting day 
irregularities were of sufficient weight to have altered the 
outcome of the elections she said 
</TEXT>
