<TEXT>
huge trucks with double or triple trailers 
could make driving more dangerous if allowed to spread to more of 
americas highways a new private group says 
we have good cause to be afraid of these rigs gerald 
donaldson a board member of citizens for reliable and safe 
highways said friday what the trucking industry wants is 
everincreasing size of trucks and everincreasing weight of 
trucks 
leaders of the group abbreviated as crash announced its 
founding at an outdoor news conference with a 100foot 
tripletrailer truck placed in front of the capitol dome as a 
backdrop 
the american trucking association in a statement said it is 
not now seeking federal legislation to allow more widespread use of 
very long trucks with triple trailers or two 48foot trailers 
they currently are restricted to certain highways in 13 western 
states 
the association said crash was making an attempt to cloak the 
rational discussion of trucking productivity in manufactured safety 
hysteria 
it said crash was inspired and funded at least indirectly 
by the railroads which it said were trying to prevent increases 
in trucking productivity and to enact unfair burdensome truck 
taxes 
paul loveday vice president of itel corp which owns and 
leases railroad boxcars told the crash news conference that his 
company gave 150000 to get the organization started 
other directors include former california gov edmund g pat 
brown former transportation secretary john volpe and joan 
claybrook former administrator of the national highway traffic 
safety administration 
if you look down the list of our board of directors i dont 
think youll see anyone on that list whos a tool of industry 
loveday said 
a statement distributed by crash said studies found double and 
tripletrailer trucks were more likely to be involved in crashes 
the trucking association said transportation department statistics 
found bigger trucks to be as safe or safer than normal trucks 
claybrook said the group would try to influence the highway bill 
congress is expected to draft next year 
she said crash also would push for stricter controls on drivers 
who use drugs or alcohol laws requiring devices on trucks to 
record their speed and hours of operation automatically and rules 
to get poorly maintained trucks off the road 
</TEXT>
