<TEXT>
mayor marion barry says hes ready to go to 
trial now that a judge refuses to drop the drug and perjury charges 
against him or to throw out medical and videotaped evidence that he 
allegedly used drugs 
defense attorneys argued on friday that the government engaged 
in prosecutorial vindictiveness by bringing six new drug charges 
against the mayor may 10 they also argued that the government 
engaged in impermissible conduct by having a cooperating government 
witness lure barry to the vista hotel on jan 18 where he 
allegedly smoked crack cocaine 
the mayor unsuccessfully sought to have the 14 criminal charges 
against him dismissed and videotape and hair sample evidence 
against him suppressed 
us district court judge thomas penfield jackson ruled that 
there was no evidence of vindictiveness he also ruled that barrys 
actions at the vista were voluntary and not coerced by the 
government 
defense r kenneth mundy used statements by a cardiologist to 
suggest that the fbi had endangered barrys life by setting up the 
sting operation 
but no violence occurred and no coercion was employed said 
jackson 
the judge did order the government to provide barry with a list 
of the alleged coconspirators and the times and places of the 
alleged cocaine possessions 
jackson also gave barry until tuesday to decide whether to seek 
a separation of the six charges brought may 10 which would result 
in a second trial at a later date 
a june 4 trial is scheduled on 10 counts of cocaine possession 
one count of conspiracy and three felony charges of lying to a 
federal grand jury 
i feel very good about today barry said after the day of 
pretrial courtroom arguments which he attended were ready to 
go to trial 
the judge said the videotape of the hotel bedroom was lawfully 
obtained with the permission of the hotel rooms occupant exmodel 
rasheeda moore 
mundy said a hair sample taken from barry after his arrest at 
the vista hotel should be excluded it tested positive for cocaine 
residue 
mundy said the residue could be from someone else and that so 
far its not a crime to be in a room where another person uses 
cocaine 
but the presence of cocaine in body specimens indicates 
relatively recent ingestion of a substance said jackson and 
may permit an inference of both a present familiarity and a 
willingness to be using it again 
jackson said he will reserve a ruling on whether the hair sample 
will be admissible evidence at trial 
