contra rebels broke off disarmament 
talks friday accusing the sandinistadominated army of killing 14 
disarmed guerrillas and 100 civilians in northern nicaragua 
the conservative government of violeta barrios de chamorro 
which succeeded the leftist sandinista administration a month ago 
but left sandinistas in charge of the military promised to look 
into the report 
contra commander oscar sobalvarro and other rebel leaders issued 
a communique initially charging that five disarmed contras were 
killed and nine others were missing after a may 18 army massacre 
near waslala in matagalpa province 150 miles northeast of managua 
defense ministry spokesman carlos lara called the charges 
totally false 
a rebel delegation raised the later charges of 14 contra and 100 
civilian dead in a friday night meeting with the government said 
roberto ferrey one of the government representatives 
if the charges bear out the government is prepared to order 
an exhaustive investigation and punishment sanctioning whoever 
turns out to be responsible said ferrey 
he said mrs chamorro ordered an onsite investigation with the 
participation of cardinal miguel obando y bravo 
the rebels learned of the incident thursday the same day that 
disarmament talks with the government got under way sobalvarro 
said in a news conference 
the talks with the government are suspended indefinitely 
until the incident is investigated and those guilty of the massacre 
of the demobilized rebels are punished the contra commander said 
lara branded the charges part of a contra propaganda campaign 
aimed at creating mistrust and insecurity among those who are 
trying to demobilize and disarm according to agreements with the 
government 
a may 4 agreement between contras and the government set a june 
10 deadline for 11000 rebels to give up their weapons 
but the contra high command suspended disarmament on may 19 and 
fewer than 1500 fighters have been demobilized to date 
sovalbarro said friday the high command will continue to 
withhold orders for disarmament 
the contras backed by the united states fought the leftist 
sandinista government in a 10year war that left 30000 dead 
rebel fighters said they would give up their arms when mrs 
chamorro backed by the united states took over the presidency 
from sandinista president daniel ortega on april 25 
but the high command changed its mind saying its troops were 
not receiving enough food housing jobs and security measures from 
the government 
the contras say their chief concern is the threat of the army 
which is controlled mostly by sandinistas 
