<TEXT>
reform judaism one of the three major jewish 
branches in the united states is considering lifting ageold 
barriers against ordaining homosexuals as rabbis 
but homosexual rabbis would be warned about dangers of making 
their sexual preference public 
reform judaism with 15 million members nationwide would be 
the first us jewish branch to take allow homosexual rabbis 
adoption of the new ordination guidelines would go against 
traditional jewish emphasis on procreation and aversion to 
homosexuality dating to prebiblical times 
the proposal was drafted by a 17member committee of the central 
conference of american rabbis representing the nations 1560 
reform rabbis after four years of study hearings and debate 
rabbi joseph b glaser the conferences executive vice 
president said friday he expects the proposal to be approved 
during the groups convention june 2428 in seattle 
its a wellbalanced statement finely tuned and sensitive to 
our concerns he said it sets a middle ground approving 
ordination of homosexuals in a roundabout way 
we ordain people who are qualified and decent and were saying 
if they happen to be gay its not any business of ours were not 
making an issue of it were saying its not an issue 
the proposal urges that all rabbis regardless of sexual 
orientation be accorded the opportunity to fulfill their sacred 
vocation which they have chosen 
but rabbis who are homosexual would be cautioned about making 
their orientation public as it can have grave professional 
consequences 
the unique position of the rabbi as spiritual leader and 
judaic role model make the acceptance of gay or lesbian rabbis an 
intensely emotional and potentially divisive issue the proposal 
said 
glaser said there was an ancient and basic jewish abhorrence 
of homosexuality derived from judaisms emphasis on procreation 
and perpetuating the human seed 
that was the first commandment he noted citing gods 
injunction in the book of genesis to be fruitful and multiply 
something impossible in homosexual unions 
the conservative wing of us judaism with 1300 rabbis and 15 
million followers advised reform colleagues against the new stand 
the orthodox branch representing an estimated 1 million followers 
also strongly condemns homosexuality 
an estimated 2 million american jews are not affiliated with any 
of the three branches of us judaism 
the proposed reform policy says 
all human beings are created betselem elohim in the divine 
image their personhood must therefore be accorded full dignity 
sexual orientation is irrelevant to the human worth of a person 
the proposed new stand is based on a recently announced 
admissions policy of reform judaisms hebrew union collegejewish 
institute of religion of cincinnati and new york 
glaser said there probably are quite a lot of homosexuals 
already in the ministry as rabbis ministers and priests 
citing scientific uncertainty about the origins of all 
homosexuality the statement says there are some people for whom 
heterosexual monogamous procreative marriage is not a viable 
option or possibility 
it adds the majority of the committee reaffirms unequivocally 
the centrality of monogamous heterosexual procreative marriage and 
its special status as kiddushin sanctified marriage 
therefore in the case of a person for whom sexual identity is 
a matter of choice the majority of the committee affirms that 
heterosexuality is the only appropriate jewish choice 
a committee minority maintained that even where choice is 
possible homosexual relationships are equally legitimate and 
that the relationship not the gender of people should determine 
its jewish value 
</TEXT>
