<TEXT>
a commodities dealer was ordered to pay 2 
million for destroying 86 acres of wetlands on his hunting retreat 
and in what the judge called restitution for birds was barred 
from hunting wild fowl 
the penalties were the largest financial sanctions ever levied 
against a person in an environmental criminal case assistant us 
attorney jane barrett said 
multimillionaire investment counselor paul tudor jones ii 35 
pleaded guilty friday in us district court to one misdemeanor 
count of violating the clean water act for filling in the wetlands 
on his maryland property with 1400 cubic yards of gravel without a 
permit 
under a plea bargain jones was fined 1 million ordered to pay 
1 million in restitution to the national fish and wildlife 
foundation and ordered to restore the 86 acres he destroyed 
barrett said 
us district judge frederick smalkin also banned jones from 
hunting migratory birds anywhere in the united states through 1991 
he was placed on 18 months probation and restricted from developing 
2500 acres of his 3272acre estate 
jones faced up to one year in prison 
wetlands are considered crucial to the health of chesapeake bay 
because they filter pollutants and provide habitat for wildlife 
the message this sends is clear that those who destroy 
wetlands will be prosecuted to the fullest extent of the law that 
is very good news for the chesapeake bay and other coastal 
waters said william baker president of the chesapeake bay 
foundation 
in a statement friday jones said the problem arose because he 
had gotten erroneous advice 
we believed in error that our experts had properly addressed 
the complex issues related to habitat development in wetlands he 
said 
breckinridge l willcox the us attorney for maryland said 
the case is the largest wetlands case ever filed in the united 
states 
jones bought the waterfront estate now valued at 20 million 
in august 1987 barrett said the property included 1742 acres of 
marshlands and wetlands at the time 
the property is northwest of the black water national wildlife 
refuge a sanctuary for geese and duck and home to one of the 
states largest populations of bald eagles 
prosecutors said jones was warned repeatedly in 1987 by his own 
consultant gregg moore to stop work at the site until he received 
permits from the army corps of engineers 
the corps told the project manager william ellen in february 
1988 after inspecting the site twice to stop filling in the 
wetlands until a permit was obtained according to court documents 
