<TEXT>
in canadas first war crimes trial a jury has 
acquitted a man charged with manslaughter and other atrocities 
against thousands of jews in nazioccupied hungary during world war 
ii jewish leaders called for a retrial 
imre finta 77 who had shown little emotion as he sat in the 
prisoners box during the sixmonth trial broke down and cried 
when he heard the verdict friday 
finta had been charged with confinement kidnapping robbery and 
manslaughter in the rounding up and deportation of 8617 jewish 
civilians from hungary in june 1944 
nobody believes finta a nazi he said sobbing after being 
cleared of all charges i love the jewish people my former 
fiancee was jewish 
the ontario supreme court jury of eight women and four men 
returned its verdict following 12 hours of deliberations over two 
days 
the native of hungary finta became a canadian citizen after the 
war and is now retired from the restaurant business in toronto he 
was a captain in the hungarian police when the jews were deported 
identification was a key question at the trial fintas lawyer 
doug christie said there was no proof finta was the uniformed 
officer some witnesses claimed had been giving orders 
the charges alleged finta was in command when the jews were 
rounded up at a brickyard in the village of szeged forced aboard 
squalid boxcars and transported to labor camps in other 
nazioccupied countries 
the simon wiesenthal center of los angeles said in a statement 
that it was deeply disappointed by the acquittal adding it 
hopes that the judicial authorities will proceed with any and all 
appeals open to them in this case 
were in a state of shock said frank dimant of bnai brith 
canada its exceptionally painful to us in light of the rising 
antisemitism internationally and in canada 
dimant executive vicepresident of the group urged canadian 
federal officials to appeal the decision and said his 
organizations lawyers are analyzing legal grounds for a retrial 
in 1986 jules deschenes the former chief justice of quebec 
superior court who headed a government inquiry into war crimes 
said there was evidence to warrant immediate prosecutions against 
at least 20 war crime suspects in canada 
the following year parliament passed its war crimes 
legislation which empowers the government to make retroactive 
warcrime charges in warassociated offenses that occurred in 
another country 
finta was the first person charged under canadas 1987 
legislation on war crimes and crimes against humanity 
the two others charged under canadas war crimes law stephen 
reistetter of st catharines ontario and michael pawlowski of 
renfrew ontario near ottawa have not yet gone to trial 
reistetter 75 is charged with kidnapping and unlawfully 
transporting 3000 jews from nazioccupied czechoslovakia while he 
was a government official during the war 
pawlowski 72 is charged in the 1942 deaths of 490 people in 
byelorussia the western soviet union 
