<TEXT>
political action committees gave 635 million 
to congressional candidates in the first 15 months of the 1990 
election cycle targeting nearly 90 percent of the specialinterest 
money to incumbents 
the 4517 pacs registered with the federal election commission 
began april with another 131 million on hand for the final six 
months of the election year the fec said in a study released 
saturday 
the 635 million in candidate contributions by pacs from 
january 1989 through march 1990 represented a 13 percent increase 
over the comparable period in the 198788 election cycle 
most of the increase came in spending on house races and was 
partly attributable to the 10 special house elections held to fill 
vacancies over the past year 
all told pacs raised 219 million and spent 173 million in the 
15 months covered by the study fund raising was up 2 percent over 
the last cycle and spending increased 7 percent 
total spending was nearly three times the amount actually 
donated to congressional candidates total spending includes 
administrative staff and new fundraising costs and in some cases 
transfers from the national pacs to affiliated state pacs for use 
in state elections 
the studys release comes as the senate considers 
campaignfinance legislation containing new limits on pac activity 
designed to erode some of the fundraising edge typically enjoyed 
by incumbents 
the fec data show pacs not only are spending more on 
congressional races but incumbents are getting even larger shares 
of the money 
in the 15 months studied incumbents got 564 million from 
pacs or 89 percent of pac candidate donations challengers 
received 32 million or just 5 percent the rest went to 
candidates in races without incumbents 
in the same 15month period of the 198788 cycle incumbents got 
88 percent of pac donations to candidates and challengers received 
65 percent two years earlier the edge was 85 percent to 7 
percent in favor of incumbents 
what this shows is that we need public financing of 
elections said joan claybrook the head of the publicinterest 
lobby public citizen pac contributions from special interests 
which want legislation enacted should not determine who gets 
elected to congress 
democrats largely because of their majorities in both chambers 
of congress received more pac money 
this years democratic senate candidates received 103 million 
from pacs through the end of march with 95 million of that total 
going to incumbent senators facing reelection gop senate 
candidates got 95 million from pacs over the same period of 
which 7 million went to incumbents 
in house races pacs gave 301 million to democratic 
candidates 28 million of it to incumbents republican candidates 
received 133 million with all but 240000 going to incumbents 
the pacs also reported contributing 103 million to national 
state and local political party organizations 
