<TEXT>
the tormented inner life of norwegian artist 
edvard munch who once said that my pictures are my diaries is 
laid bare in a new exhibition of his prints opening sunday at the 
national gallery of art 
the shows 94 prints were assembled from the holdings of sarah 
and lionel epstein of washington dc who plan eventually to give 
their entire collection of about 200 munch woodcuts lithographs 
and other graphic works to the national gallery 
gallery officials say the epsteins who began collecting his 
prints in 1961 have the largest and finest collection of munchs 
graphic works outside europe 
to mark the shows opening the epsteins gave the gallery two of 
the prints on display they are the kiss a color woodcut made 
in 1902 and madonna a color woodcut combined with lithograph 
made in the same year which presents an ambiguous image of 
religious or sexual ecstasy 
the prints reveal the turbulent feelings of anger jealousy 
loneliness anxiety fear and sexual desire that haunted munch for 
much of his life his recurring artistic themes such as sick 
children and estranged couples reflected his own romantic 
conflicts and the traumatic deaths of his parents and siblings 
senior curator andrew robison said munch like his contemporary 
sigmund freud portrays the life of his inner self his emotions 
and dreams 
munchs approach to life through his art and innovative print 
techniques was highly influential among german expressionists 
gallery director j carter brown called munch who died in 1944 
one of the great talents of modern western civilization 
the exhibition titled edvard munch master prints from the 
epstein family collection will appear at the national gallery 
through sept 3 
it will travel to honolulu los angeles miami indianapolis 
kansas city mo atlanta and memphis tenn through january 1992 
the exhibition is underwritten by statoil the norwegian 
national oil company 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

