here are some facts and figures about burmas national election 
to be held sunday 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
at stake the first multiparty elections in burma since 1960 
are for 492 seats in a parliament that will draft a new 
constitution once this is done the ruling military has promised 
to step down from power 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
voting there are nearly 21 million eligible voters including 
26 million in rangoon the capital all citizens 18 years old and 
above can vote a complete election tally will not be available for 
up to three weeks 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
supervision some groups have charged the election will be 
rigged the military maintains it will be fair and free an 
election commission says ballots will be counted at each of the 
18190 polling stations with candidates representatives present 
foreign monitoring will be minimal several human rights and 
legal groups asked to observe the election but have not received 
visas rangoon has allowed more than 60 american asian and 
european journalists into the country which has been virtually 
offlimits to the foreign press since mid1989 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
main parties and candidates contesting the election are 2296 
candidates from 93 parties along with 87 independents 
the national unity party fielding 490 candidates is widely 
believed to have military backing the best organized and financed 
it is the least popular under the name of the burma socialist 
program party it led burma to economic ruin during a 
quartercentury of oneparty rule 
the national league for democracy fielding 448 candidates is 
the strongest of the prodemocracy parties although its two key 
leaders aung san suu kyi and tin oo have been barred from 
participating in the elections 
other parties which stand to make a showing are the league for 
democracy and peace backed by onetime prime minister nu the union 
nationals democracy party of aung gyi thu wais democracy party 
and the democratic front for national reconstruction headed by 
