executives at a denver television station have 
defended their staffs videotaping of an illegal pit bull fight as 
legitimate newsgathering activities 
roger ogden general manager of kcnctv on friday said station 
employees attended such a fight in september but they didnt 
realize at the time that it was illegal 
he also said the tape used in reporter wendy bergens fourpart 
series on illegal pit bull fights came from a confidential source 
we have been told and we believe that this video was not the 
same fight attended by kcnc employees in september the station 
said in a statement 
the station and police agencies began an investigation this 
month after allegations were made by anonymous sources that kcnc 
staged a fight between two dogs for bergens series the sources 
also told competing news organizations the station paid for the 
fight 
kcnctv denied the allegations and ogden ordered a 
comprehensive investigation 
police said the fight featured in bergens report which aired 
april 30 through may 2 occurred on a grassy area near the south 
platte river in sheridan a denver suburb 
staging a dogfight or even attending one is a felony in 
colorado punishable by up to four years in prison and 1000 fine 
police investigations into the incident were completed this 
week district attorneys in arapahoe and jefferson counties where 
the fights reportedly occurred are looking into who might have 
been involved 
no charges have been filed against station employees or dog 
owners kcnctv news director marv rockford said no disciplinary 
action has been taken against any kcnc employee 
in a statement released friday kcnc defended its actions 
we believe the subject of pit bulls and pit bull fighting in 
colorado was and is a legitimate topic of public concern and 
interest and is an appropriate journalistic subject the unsigned 
statement said 
last september in the course of investigating the pit bull 
issue kcnc employees attended and videotaped a pit bull fight that 
took place in arapahoe county attendance and coverage of the fight 
was in the normal course of the stations activity in gathering the 
news and preparing the report the station later learned of the 
existence of a criminal statute relating to dogfighting 
we then contacted and met with robert gallagher the district 
attorney for arapahoe county and members of his staff to discuss 
whether journalists attending and videotaping a pit bull fight for 
the purpose of obtaining and reporting the news might be committing 
a criminal act 
while they indicated that it was their view that the statute 
might apply even in that situation kcnc did not and does not agree 
with any interpretation of the statute that would make criminal 
such legitimate newsgathering activities 
when the arapahoe county district attorneys office learned of 
kcncs statement it announced that a special prosecutor would be 
appointed to review the case 
but because of the holiday weekend it will be at least tuesday 
before the court appoints a special prosecutor 
