<TEXT>
yugoslavias communist party on 
saturday called for nationwide multiparty elections and formally 
renounced its monopoly on political power at a national congress 
but the congress was boycotted by communist party members from 
three of yugoslavias six constituent republics and analysts said 
it is doubtful the latest moves by the party will help restore its 
sagging national power 
in a rare commentary the leading macedonian daily nova 
makedonija said saturdays session represents the definite end 
of the communist party of yugoslavia since only three of the six 
republics took part in the session 
delegates from slovenia croatia and macedonia refused to join 
in the resumption of the 14th communist party congress that broke 
up in disarray at its last meeting in january 
communists suffered resounding defeats in recent local 
multiparty elections in slovenia and croatia the first free 
elections in yugoslavia in 50 years 
delegates from the three republics that boycotted the meeting 
claimed the resumed congress was organized by hardliners intent on 
maintaining their leading role at a time when parts of the country 
are already moving toward democracy 
the january congress was suspended when slovenias delegates 
left the hall after losing a vote on reforms to hardliners 
participating in saturdays gathering were communists from 
serbia the largest republic montenegro and bosniahercegovina 
delegates at the threehour session adopted a statement waiving 
the partys leading role in society and called for free national 
elections 
the most important thing is that the party be radically 
reformed into a modern political party said communist party 
acting president miomir grbovic in his opening speech 
yugoslavias communist party continues to rule at the federal 
level but its power has been crippled since centerright parties 
won elections in slovenia and croatia 
multiparty elections are also planned in bosniahercegovina and 
macedonia 
many political analysts doubt the communist party can restore 
the authority it has lost after over a decade of ethnic and 
political squabbles and economic mismanagement 
saturdays session decided that a congress of democratic 
renewal will be held on september 29 and the communist party will 
take part in future free elections at the federal level 
the adopted document said the radically renewed party will 
try to unite all leftist political groups within yugoslavia 
the party still enjoys the support of the working class and 
will continue to rely on it in the future grbovic said but he 
admitted the partys reputation has drastically declined 
throughout yugoslavia 
