<TEXT>
the bloodiest election campaign in 
colombias 180 years of independence comes to a close with sundays 
presidential voting but many feared that the terror unleashed by 
drug traffickers would continue 
officials accused the drug barons of using violence to keep 
people away from the polls the army and police mobilized 230000 
troops for electionday duty and military checkpoints lined major 
streets and highways 
just hours before the polls were to open president virgilio 
barco exhorted colombians to vote in defiance of the terrorism 
to vote is to support democracy to reject violence and to 
defend the rights that the terrorists want to snatch from us 
barco said in his nationally broadcast speech 
he added i do not have the slightest doubt that both the 
terrorist acts aimed at taking the lives of presidential candidates 
as well as those committed against other compatriots have been 
carried out to intimidate the popular will 
some colombians said they planned to vote early to cut the 
time spent standing in line thus reducing the risk of being killed 
or maimed in an attack 
colombias drug war has overshadowed every other issue in the 
presidential campaign 
in the past nine months three presidential candidates 262 
policemen 93 soldiers three judges 15 news media employees and 
about 1700 other people have been slain 
bombs have exploded at schools churches shopping centers and 
supermarkets one bomb destroyed a colombian airliner killing all 
107 people aboard 
in the two weeks leading up to sundays balloting nine bombs 
exploded in four colombian cities killing 37 people and wounding 
more than 320 
few of the crimes have been solved but suspicion for most of 
the killings has fallen on drug traffickers who have private 
armies and billions of dollars in cocaine profits at their disposal 
rightwing death squads and leftist guerrillas also have played 
roles in the carnage 
the army and police said 230000 troops would be out in force 
for the election and a curfew was imposed in the drug capital of 
medellin following a wave of bombings and murders 
government officials have expressed fears that intimidation by 
traffickers would prevent some people from voting and accused the 
drug lords of stepping up attacks to scare people there are about 
138 million eligible voters 
barco and his wife planned to vote as soon as the polls opened 
as is traditional for the president barcos fouryear term ends 
aug 7 and the constitution prohibits a president from serving two 
successive terms 
there are 12 candidates for president only four are considered 
to have nationwide backing 
the ruling liberal partys candidate cesar gaviria is 
considered the leading contender he is the only candidate who has 
promised to continue barcos tough policies against the 
traffickers including extradition of drug traffickers to the 
united states 
gaviria replaced the partys frontrunning presidential 
contender luis carlos galan who was assassinated last aug 18 
it was the killing of galan which authorities blamed on 
traffickers that set off the governments offensive against the 
drug trade including the resumption of the governments 
extradition policy 
one main presidential contender alvaro gomez has urged 
legalization of cocaine in the major drugconsuming countries he 
says the only way to put the traffickers out of business is to 
deprive them of profits 
gomez an independent and the other two main candidates 
rodrigo lloreda and navarro wolf all say they would likely stop 
the extraditions the barco government has extradited 15 drug 
suspects to the united states in the past nine months 
gaviria says he would continue extraditions at least until 
colombia is able to put traffickers in jail and keep them there 
no other issue claimed anything approaching the attention given 
to the drug war 
the traffickers dark shadow of terrorism has blotted out all 
other issues said enrique santos whose family owns the bogota 
daily el tiempo colombias largest newspaper there is nothing 
philosophical about this election 
indeed the candidates have scarcely mentioned such pressing 
issues as unemployment inflation and the need for land reform 
unemployment is running 9 percent according to government 
figures private economists say it is 20 percent inflation is 
running at 28 percent up from 26 percent last year 
clara lopez a former bogota city council president says 
drugrelated violence poses less of a threat than social injustice 
which she says could lead to unrest 
all of colombias problems originate with the inequitable 
distribution of land said lopez a human rights activist who has 
campaigned for constitutional reforms 
colombians also decide sunday whether a constituent assembly 
should be named to consider changes in the 1886 constitution 
proponents of the assembly say the constitution must be altered to 
make the judicial system stronger and to break up large land 
holdings 
according to a 1970 census the last that tracked land 
distribution ownership of 68 percent of the land is concentrated 
in the hands of 43 percent of the population 
but even that problem goes back to drug traffickers the army 
has said traffickers own millions of acres of land 
gaviria and other presidential candidates following barcos 
lead have insisted that the root of the problem lies with the 
insatiable appetite for cocaine in other countries especially in 
the united states 
