rain strong winds and lightning 
saturday knocked out power to about 5000 people swelled rivers 
blew over trees and whipped up a tornado authorities said 
no injuries or deaths were reported in the severe storm which 
included a funnel cloud sighted in a small rural community in 
fayette county about 30 miles southeast of charleston 
the storm left about 5000 people in five counties without power 
before it subsided saturday night meteorologist barry gooden of 
the national weather service said more rain was expected in the 
area sunday 
jack shaver a spokesman for appalachian power co said high 
winds knocked trees into power lines and downed some poles 
emergency crews were sent out to restore service by early sunday 
he said 
the state police said in a written statement that a tornado 
touched down in the gauley bridge community where trees were blown 
over power lines were downed and streets were covered by up to 3 
feet of water 
a tree knocked a power line onto the roof of the state police 
office at gauley bridge cutting electricity and telephone service 
the statement said 
a dispatcher for the fayette county sheriffs department said no 
stormrelated injuries or deaths were reported the gauley bridge 
fire department also had no such reports 
