<TEXT>
chinas political repression hasnt altered the shift schedule 
for workers making barbie doll accessories near canton mcdonnell 
douglas jetliners outside shanghai or jeep cherokees in beijing 
but for other american businesses ranging from defense 
contractor grumman corp to tourism outfits like lindblad travel 
the consequences of the yearold crackdown on dissent have been 
disappointing or worse 
their experiences show the mixed impact of the crushed tiananmen 
uprising on the hundreds of us companies and investors that have 
sought a foothold in the worlds most populous nation since it 
emerged from isolation a decade ago 
china has always been difficult to generalize about its a 
huge place said jerome alan cohen a china specialist in the 
hong kong office of the international law firm paul weiss rifkind 
wharton amp garrison 
trade continues to go up investment is plainly down said 
cohen whose firm advises american and other foreign clients you 
have fewer new projects coming into the pipeline the results are 
only gradually becoming apparent 
other uschina specialists and business executives generally 
agree the combination of a political chill and a severe economic 
decline have made the country a more difficult place for foreign 
companies the past year 
many pending deals have stalled or unraveled new investment has 
tumbled and the longterm outlook for improvement remains unclear 
american visitors have slowed to a trickle 
uschinese commercial relations warmed somewhat on may 24 
when president bush extended chinas mostfavorednation trading 
status for a year 
the move aimed at protecting 18 billion in twoway trade was 
welcomed by us farmers toymakers and textile importers who stood 
to suffer had bush done otherwise 
american business attitudes toward china have hardened 
nevertheless any illusions that american entrepreneurs may have 
harbored about the potential of this market of a billion consumers 
were shattered by last junes violence 
no one is saying hey china theres something we havent 
looked at yet said richard brecher manager of the investor 
advisory program for the united stateschina business council a 
washingtonbased group that promotes american business interests in 
china 
at the same time brecher said i think theres a sense among 
most of the business community that were dealing with a 
transitional government its a matter of holding on now 
weathering the storm 
no us company operating in china before june has departed 
many say that after a shortlived disruption a year ago their 
operations there are normal or close to it 
at mattels two factories in southern guangdong province for 
example output of barbie accessories disney items and preschool 
products accounts for about 20 percent of the toy giants business 
spokesman glenn bozarth said 
although the company could have switched production to other 
factories in malaysia mexico or europe under an emergency 
contingency plan last june he said we didnt invoke that 
because there wasnt a need 
at mcdonnell douglas corps operation near shanghai where 
chinese workers assemble md80 jetliners the production schedule 
recently was extended by 20 aircraft the operation one of chinas 
largest manufacturing ventures with a us company began in 1985 
with a longterm contract to assemble 25 md80s 
the fact is china has a very large requirement for 
airplanes said donald hanson spokesman for the companys 
douglas aircraft subsidiary as for the political mood in the 
country i dont think i can say its had any major impact he 
said 
but some other highprofile ventures have slowed down chrysler 
corp has been forced to scale back the production schedule at its 
jeep assembly plant in the chinese capital largely because of 
chinas economic austerity controls spokeswoman karen stewart said 
we havent gone backwards but havent gone forward as much as 
we would have liked she said with china our policy is were 
there to stay for the long haul you reach ebbs and flows 
grumman corp suffered when china scrapped a 2568 million 
contract to modernize chinese jet fighters with equipment built by 
the defense contractor 
the midmay cancellation was an indirect result of the bush 
administrations suspension of military sales to the country last 
year still said company spokesman weyman b jones grumman 
remains a partner in a joint venture near shanghai that plans to 
produce 500 fire trucks a year 
last year us companies signed 268 contracts for joint 
ventures and other projects 43 more than a year earlier but 
practically all 1989 contracts were completed before june and new 
ventures definitely have stalled 
between june and december clearly there was a downturn 
said charles j conroy a partner at baker amp mckenzie a law firm 
that represents many businesses with interests in china 
conroy said some american companies have since begun to quietly 
explore new opportunities in china but he said theyre not 
megabilliondollar investments like new airports or port 
infrastructure 
perhaps the biggest us business victims of the past year have 
been tour operators most were overwhelmed by cancellations last 
summer their busiest time of year and face another dismal summer 
this year 
united airlines and northwest airlines the two us carriers to 
china have both cut flights to one a week because of slack demand 
the reason why people arent going is not because theyre 
afraid its moral indignation about what happened there said 
lars eric lindblad whose lindblad travel company pioneered 
largescale us tours to china but folded in october partly the 
result of mass cancellations 
lindblad nevertheless plans to lead a 484passenger ocean cruise 
lines tour to china on june 21 the first big us vacation group 
to visit the country since the tiananmen uprising he said the tour 
is fully booked 
other tour operators said theyve picked up some china business 
mostly for the fall many expect tourism to resume in earnest 
eventually but most are still smarting from the wallop they 
received a year ago 
the group business just dropped everyone canceled said 
patricia cunneen head of eastquest a small new yorkbased travel 
concern that specializes in adventurous trips to asia 
although her company survived she said a lot of businesses 
have closed they call it the tiananmen massacre here 
</TEXT>
