<TEXT>
when mikhail bernstam taught economics in 
leningrad 20 years ago and expressed some distinctly nonmarxist 
ideas his colleagues gave him puzzled worried looks 
my friends barely understood me they thought i was crazy 
says bernstam now a senior fellow at the hoover institution on the 
stanford university campus 
soviet president mikhail gorbachevs postsummit visit monday to 
hoover a longtime bastion of anticommunism will give bernstam 
the chance finally to offer his crazy notions to a more 
receptive countryman 
bernstam and five other scholars at hoover the think tank that 
spawned the economic principles and some key figures in the reagan 
and bush administrations will offer papers to gorbachev 
suggesting ways of solving the soviet unions enormous economic 
problems 
if gorbachev is coming to stanford for advice and san francisco 
for business hell find plenty of people eager to accommodate him 
though more than a few are skeptical of the success of his reform 
program 
the academic and corporate communities playing host to gorbachev 
expect him to make a strong pitch for support in converting the 
soviet economy to a freemarket system 
the visit has charged the bay area with a super bowl atmosphere 
sending corporate executives scrambling for a chance to dine with 
him at a business luncheon some willing to pay thousands of 
dollars for a ticket 
fifteen companies cosponsoring the event are paying 2000 for 
two seats each and up to 500 for additional seats labor leaders 
are complaining they may be left out 
