chevron will attend the luncheon 
rep tom campbell rcalif said the soviets have a desperate 
need for computers fax machines modems and other hightech 
office equipment that are attracting them to silicon valley and 
the interest is mutual 
we are very concerned about losing one of the largest markets 
well ever see said campbell who fears european and asian 
companies will swoop in on the soviets if american firms move too 
slowly 
i dont see any risk to our defense and i do see economic 
benefits one of the great dreams is well be so integrated 
economically that nobody would benefit from an attack he said 
gorbachevs visit is more than a public relations gesture 
said bill johnston palo altobased hewlettpackards director of 
international planning and administration he is clearly wooing 
the west and certainly this area hes trying to get his economy 
squared away and attract us manufacturing expertise to the soviet 
union 
hewlettpackard has had an office in moscow for 18 years and 
last week joined four other us companies in a consortium with 
three soviet health and medical research ministries 
there are a lot of problems johnston said the currency 
is a major issue there is still considerable political and 
economic uncertainty and the two are interlocked they have a mess 
on their hands 
to help gorbachev clean up the mess hoover scholars will offer 
their ideas and willingness to join with soviet officials to 
reshape the country 
the onepage summaries offered to gorbachev who was lured to 
