<TEXT>
a baltic cloud hangs over the ussoviet 
summit as pressure builds on lithuania to suspend its declaration 
of independence and return at least temporarily to the soviet 
fold 
soviet president mikhail s gorbachev and president bush both 
hopeful of making progress on arms control and other issues may 
find the baltics a needling irritant when they begin a fourday 
summit thursday 
but gorbachev may be moving to disperse what bush calls a 
cloud of tension over the three baltic republics proclamations 
of independence 
if gorbachev succeeds the summit forecast could be much sunnier 
late last week gorbachev said that if lithuania suspended its 
march 11 declaration he would lift his punishing economic embargo 
and even compensate lithuanians for its damage 
the soviet president also offered a road map for lithuanian 
independence saying it could be achieved under kremlin rules 
within two years three years earlier than he had said previously 
in a meeting with lithuanian lawmakers in moscow gorbachev did 
not repeat his previous insistence that independence be sought only 
under the terms of a soviet secession law 
that law which baltic leaders dub the law to prevent 
secession permits independence only after a fiveyear 
coolingoff period 
but gorbachev paired last weeks carrot with a heavy stick 
vowing to impose direct presidential rule on lithuania if the 
independence declaration was not suspended 
if he imposed presidential rule gorbachev could disband 
lithuanias parliament its first freely elected legislature in 50 
years replace the lithuanian government with moscowappointed 
officials and impose martial law 
the lithuanian parliament has so far offered only to suspend the 
effect of laws to implement independence and has adamantly refused 
to freeze the independence declaration itself 
balticamericans will use the summit to dramatize the cause of 
lithuania latvia and estonia all of which lost their independence 
in a 1940 secret deal between josef stalin and adolf hitler 
a rally is planned in lafayette park across from the white house 
before gorbachevs arrival one lithuanian group will demonstrate 
outside the soviet embassy another will conduct a candlelight 
vigil there two mass demonstrations are planned on the steps of 
the capitol 
bush acknowledged last week that the independence crisis 
certainly puts some tension on the summit and said he was 
unhappy about the state of play in the baltics 
but bush has also said repeatedly that his discussions with 
gorbachev on nuclear arms control are too important to be derailed 
secretary of state james a baker iii said recently the 
independence crisis does cast a long shadow but he says the 
administration is determined to prevent the summits eclipse 
there is too much at stake to dismiss cavalierly the 
potential for progress in ussoviet relations baker said 
the euphoria that flared from baltic expatriots worldwide when 
lithuania issued its ringing declaration of independence evaporated 
in the warning rumble of soviet tanks through the streets of 
vilnius and in gorbachevs orders to slow to a trickle the flow of 
oil and natural gas into the republic 
but the soviet economic embargo did not discourage the thirst 
for independence there or in neighboring latvia and estonia 
the estonian parliament on march 30 branded the soviet union an 
occupying power and vowed to restore full independence over time 
on may 4 the latvian parliament followed suit declaring 
independence while trying to avoid an outright clash with moscow by 
postponing the effective date pending completion of negotiations 
baltic leaders have contended that agreeing to gorbachevs 
original demand that they seek independence under soviet law would 
be to concede their incorporation into the soviet union was legal 
in the first place 
admitting that we must quit the soviet union under soviet law 
would be to lose our most important asset our status as an 
occupied country said tunne v kelam chairman of the council of 
estonia the executive committee of estonias independent 
parliament 
when you are raped and robbed you cannot ask for legal 
divorce you were never married kelam said in an interview 
during a recent us visit 
the three baltic republics have long been known in conservative 
circles in the united states as the captive nations outside 
the balticamerican community the most intense domestic pressure 
on bush to embrace the independence cause has come from this 
direction 
bush and baker have voiced a doubleedged policy toward the 
baltics 
over 50 years the united states has never recognized the 
forced incorporation of the three republics into the soviet union 
it does not do so now 
but the united states will not extend formal diplomatic 
recognition until those republics control their own territory 
institutions and political destiny 
with a highstakes agenda before him bush decided not to impose 
sanctions against the soviets to make gorbachev pay a price for his 
embargo against lithuania 
upset by that decision the senate on may 2 voted 7324 to put 
bush on notice that congressional approval of a new ussoviet 
trade agreement prized by moscow is unlikely until the embargo is 
lifted and talks begin on lithuanian independence 
kazimiera prunskiene an economist and lithuanias elected prime 
minister said repeatedly during a us visit last month that the 
west held the key to independence 
her prescription increase economic and political pressure on 
gorbachev to free the baltic republics while at the same time 
encouraging the democratic reforms fostered by gorbachevs glasnost 
openness and perestroika economic restructuring 
a democratized soviet union she reasons will not cling to 
formerly independent nations annexed against their peoples will 
dmitri simes an exiled soviet scholar who is a senior associate 
of the carnegie endowment for international peace contends the 
real choice gorbachev faces is not between perestroika and 
lithuanian independence but between building soviet democracy and 
saving the vast and rickety soviet domain 
but many western leaders fault lithuania for moving too rapidly 
for giving fuel to gorbachevs conservative opposition 
west german chancellor helmut kohl and french president francois 
mitterrand have urged lithuania to suspend its declaration of 
independence and follow the dictates of the soviet independence law 
the bush administration has all but endorsed this approach 
nudging the baltic republics to accept it 
gorbachev told baker in moscow earlier in the month that 
domestic pressures are such that he does not have a lot of room 
to maneuver on the baltic crisis 
there the stalemate stands 
vytautas landsbergis the president of the lithuanian 
parliament urged his countrymen last week to hold on and to 
survive as though we were in a surrounded fortress 
meanwhile he and the leaders of latvia and estonia have 
appealed to bush and gorbachev to take our problems into their 
hearts as they view the world from the summits heights 
</TEXT>
