<TEXT>
commodity brokers and their customers are the big winners in the 
agreement by chicagos giant futures exchanges to share an 
electronic trading system 
the unusual pact between the chicago board of trade and the 
chicago mercantile exchange means the futures industry will avoid 
the high costs of duplicate networks costs that ultimately would 
be passed on to customers and the hassle of learning two systems 
david vogel chairman of the futures industry association also 
agreed with the benefit touted by the exchanges when they announced 
the agreement this past wednesday by uniting instead of competing 
the chicago markets stand a better chance of maintaining their 
dominance of global futures trading as financial markets everywhere 
move toward roundtheclock trading 
it looks like 24hour electronic trading is going to come 
about and it will be multinational and competitive in nature 
said vogel chief executive officer of lit america inc a new york 
futures trading concern 
i think its very important that americans be competitive 
here he said 
ever since the merc developed world currency futures in the 
early 1970s touching off a worldwide explosion of financial 
futures and options products the chicago exchanges have seen 
global access as the key to continued us leadership in the 
expanding marketplace 
the problem can be boiled down to two words time zones tokyo 
is about 16 hours ahead of chicago and london is six hours ahead 
to attract business from both of those important financial centers 
the chicago markets ideally would have to be open around the clock 
the board of trade initiated a threehour night trading session 
for interestrate futures early in 1987 to catch the opening of the 
japanese business day the exchange has declared night trading a 
success but concedes it would be impractical to keep its trading 
floor open 24 hours 
in the fall of 1987 the merc announced a different approach in 
partnership with londonbased reuters holdings plc the merc would 
create an automated trading system called globex that would operate 
when its trading floor is closed 
globex would enable traders around the world to buy and sell the 
mercs products and those of other exchanges that chose to 
participate by tapping orders into computer terminals supplied by 
reuters the orders would be matched by a central computer often 
called a black box 
the board of trade initially opposed the concept and asked 
regulators to block it but early last year the board of trade said 
it would develop its own electronic trading system dubbed aurora 
unlike the blind tradematching technology of globex auroras 
screen would mimic a commodity trading pit and enable users to 
select their trading partners the board of trade contended this 
was a superior concept and earmarked 25 million to develop the 
system 
but critics said aurora would be more susceptible to trading 
abuse many brokers led by the futures industry association 
clamored for a single system 
last may the exchanges agreed to explore the possibility of a 
shared system 
the fia from the very beginning promoted this dialogue and 
made it very clear that a single or shared system is what they 
desire vogel said 
the agreement announced by the exchanges does not explain how 
the system will be shared but it does say reuters will be 
involved prompting speculation it will be a black box system and 
that aurora will exist only as a name under which the board of 
trades products will be offered 
the exchanges said they expect the system to be fully 
operational by november 
