<TEXT>
he lied more than he could remember got a big 
tax break from cheating the stock market kept an illegal fortune 
out of government hands and bribed fellow felons with pocket change 
to do his dirty laundry 
those were among the new details that embellished the portrait 
of former stock speculator ivan f boesky under harsh questioning 
in a manhattan federal courtroom this past week and he wasnt even 
on trial 
the gaunt 53yearold inside trader central figure in the 
biggest criminal scandal in wall street history premiered as a 
star prosecution witness in the trial of john a mulheren jr a 
former friend and wall street professional accused of securities 
fraud 
boeskys first public appearance since completing a federal 
prison term last month had been eagerly awaited largely because it 
finally afforded someone hed implicated in his crimes the 
opportunity to confront him 
the faceoff between boesky and mulherens attorney thomas 
puccio riddled with terse and acidic exchanges provided more 
drama than scriptwriters for la law could ever have 
concocted it was a defense lawyers dream 
puccio spent hours seeking to skewer boeskys moral values and 
his selfportrait as a reformed impoverished and humbled exbaron 
of the stock market whod paid his debt to society 
the witness admitted hed lied repeatedly to investigators 
before his plea bargain and took a tax deduction for half his 100 
million insider trading settlement with the government in 1986 
he also admitted the settlement didnt include profits hed 
earned from other insider trading which by some estimates total 
many millions of dollars 
one of the more telling admissions came in a seemingly innocuous 
detail about his life in the lompoc federal prison camp where he 
spent two years asked if hed broken any rules there boesky 
admitted improperly paying other inmates quarters to wash his 
clothes the new york tabloid press seized on it 
boesky cleans up and twobit boesky screamed the 
headlines in the new york post the daily news called it ivans 
dirty laundry 
lawyers following the case said puccio may have succeeded in 
undermining boeskys credibility but that did not mean mulheren 
was any closer to acquittal he faces 41 counts of securities 
fraud mail fraud and other crimes 
ultimately the question for the jury is not ivan boesky alone 
its going to be government witnesses in the aggregate said john 
c coffee jr a columbia law school professor id be very 
surprised if the government rested its factual allegations on just 
boeskys sayso 
stanley arkin a wellknown defense attorney who has represented 
several traders implicated in the wall street fraud scandal said 
federal prosecutors may have made boesky testify early in the trial 
so the jury would forget about him after a couple of weeks 
when the government feels it might have a credibility problem 
with a witness they want to put him on first and get it over 
with arkin said its the strategy of letting time and other 
things heal the inadequacy of the lead witness 
others said it was possible jurors would focus on boeskys 
performance because it was a dramatic point in an otherwise 
complicated trial some said boeskys admissions about his life and 
his image as a squealer who cut a deal to save himself could be 
quite damaging to the governments case 
boesky sounds like hes being as evasive as hell said 
michael feldberg a new york defense attorney and former federal 
prosecutor it sounds like hes not being terribly candid just 
from the impression hes given but ultimately the jurys going to 
decide that 
